Divide: Urban Peripheries as Sites of Food Sovereignty Construction in Caracas -- tPART 4 Extended Urbanization between New Rurality and Operational Landscapes -- t11 Planetary Urbanization, Agro-Exports, and Informality: Making Sense of the Expanding Peripheries and Emerging Cities in Coastal Ecuador -- t12 Worlding the Atacama Desert: Peripheral Urbanization and Transnational Resource Extraction Urbanism in Antofagasta, Chile -- t13 Planetary Urbanization and Maquiladoras: Unveiling Abstract Space in Yucatán, Mexico -- t14 Rural Livelihoods, Urbanization, and Incomplete Population Transitions in Brazil -- t15 The Urbanization of Mexico’s Countryside: A Socio-political Approach to Spatial Transformation -- tConclusion: Peripheral Urbanization: Current Trends, Methodological Advances, and the Decolonization of Urban Theo -- tContributors -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aBeyond the Megacity connects and reconnects the global debate on the contemporary urban condition to the Latin American tradition of seeing, considering, and theorizing urbanization from the margins. It develops the approach of "peripheral urbanization" as a way to integrate the theoretical agendas belonging to global suburbanisms, neo-marxist accounts of planetary urbanization, and postcolonial urban studies, and to move urban theory closer to the complexity and diversity of urbanization in the Global South. From an interdisciplinary perspective, Beyond the Megacity investigates the natures, causes, implications, and politics of current urbanization processes in Latin America. The book draws on case studies from various countries across the region covering different theoretical and disciplinary approaches from the fields of geography, anthropology, sociology, urban studies, agrarian studies, and urban and regional planning, and is written by academics, journalists, practitioners, and scholar-activists. Beyond the Megacity unites these unique perspectives by shifting attention to the places, processes, practices, and bodies of knowledge that have often been neglected in the past.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jun 2022) 0aUrbanizationzLatin AmericavCase studies. 7aARCHITECTURE / Urban & Land Use Planning.2bisacsh  aLatin America.  aactivism.  adecolonial.  aeconomy.  aextractivism.  amovements.  aperipheries.  apolitics.  apostcolonial.  arurality.  asocial.  asururb.  asururban.  atheory.  aurban.  aurbanism.  aurbanization.1 aAlfaro, Claudia Fonseca, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aArboleda, Martín, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBarbieri, Alisson F., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBayón, Manuel, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCaldeira, Teresa, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCastriota, Rodrigo, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDurán, Gustavo, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFelicien, Ana, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGolda-Pongratz, Kathrin, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLukas, Michael, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLukas, Michael, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aMason-Deese, Liz, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMenoscal, Jonathan, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMoeller, Hannah-Hunt, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aOjima, Ricardo, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ct